          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"week_number\":1,\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weekly_target_km\":40,\"is_deload_week\":false,\"days\":[{\"day_of_week\":0,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"notes\":\"Long easy run at 5:50–6:27/km. Keep it conversational — this is about time on feet, not pace. Aim for 14 km as a comfortable starting point.\"},{\"day_of_week\":1,\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Full rest day. Sleep, hydrate, and let Sunday's work absorb. Recovery is where the adaptation happens.\"},{\"day_of_week\":2,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"Easy run at 5:50–6:27/km, around 8 km. Focus on relaxed form and steady breathing. No heroics today.\"},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"slot_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"workout_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"notes\":\"Low-impact cross-training: cycling, swimming, or yoga. 30–45 min. Great opportunity to address hip mobility given your IT band history.\"},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"notes\":\"Tempo run: 2 km easy warm-up, then 20 min at threshold pace (4:50/km), 2 km easy cool-down. Total ~8 km. This builds your lactate threshold — your most important half-marathon fitness lever.\"},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Rest day. Back-to-back quality and rest keeps the stress-recovery cycle working. Trust the process.\"},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"Easy 10 km at 5:50–6:27/km. Shake out the legs and finish the week feeling fresh, not fried.\"}],\"week_summary\":\"Welcome to Week 1, Lee — and a strong starting point you've got. Your 10K result gives us a VDOT of 42, and your recent consistency (33–34 km over the last couple of weeks) means we're building on a real foundation, not starting from scratch. This first week holds you at your current volume of 40 km while we establish the rhythm of the plan: a Sunday long run, one quality session mid-week (tempo), cross-training to support your IT band health, and easy running to fill the aerobic tank. Every pace this week should feel manageable — if the tempo feels hard but doable, you're exactly where you need to be. The goal right now is aerobic base and durability. Speed comes later. What's your gut feeling about the tempo distance as a starting point?\"}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
